 a marginal activity, but one essential to the articulation of the abbey's image. This text also participates in a vibrant post-Conquest textual culture, in particular at Canterbury, including the writing of the bilingual F version of the Chronicle; its symbiotic relationship witha wider corpus of Latin historiography thus indicates the presence of shared sources. The incorporation of alternative generic types in the text also suggests the presence of formal hybridity, a further testament to a fluid and adaptable textual culture. Dr Malasree Home teaches at Newcastle University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAnglo-SaxonsxHistoriography. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAbbey's Image.  aAnglo-Saxon Chronicle.  aBilingual F Version.  aChronicle Tradition.  aCommunal Identity.  aLatin Historiography.  aMedieval Texts.  aPeterborough Abbey.  aPost-Conquest History.  aTextual Culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204469740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782044697423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782044697/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles